{
  "lesson_number": 18,
  "title": "Lesson 18",
  "topic": "Feminine nouns ending in -ā",
  "grammar": {
    "explanations": [
      "Feminine nouns ending in -ā are declined according to the pattern of vanitā (woman). Most nouns ending in -ā are feminine.",
      "In the singular, the nominative ends in -ā, the vocative in -e, the accusative in -aṃ, and the instrumental, ablative, dative, genitive, and locative all share the ending -āya (with an optional -āyaṃ for the locative).",
      "In the plural, the nominative/vocative takes -ā or -āyo, the accusative takes -ā or -āyo, the instrumental takes -āhi (or -ābhi), the dative/genitive takes -ānaṃ, and the locative takes -āsu."
    ],
    "tables": [
      {
        "title": "Declension of vanitā (woman) - Singular",
        "rows": [
          ["Nom.", "vanitā"],
          ["Voc.", "vanite"],
          ["Acc.", "vanitaṃ"],
          ["Ins.", "vanitāya"],
          ["Abl.", "vanitāya"],
          ["Dat.", "vanitāya"],
          ["Gen.", "vanitāya"],
          ["Loc.", "vanitāya, vanitāyaṃ"]
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "Declension of vanitā (woman) - Plural",
        "rows": [
          ["Nom./Voc.", "vanitā, vanitāyo"],
          ["Acc.", "vanitā, vanitāyo"],
          ["Ins.", "vanitāhi (vanitābhi)"],
          ["Dat./Gen.", "vanitānaṃ"],
          ["Loc.", "vanitāsu"]
        ]
      }
    ],
    "examples": []
  },
